This line: const { login } = useAuth();

is equivalent to:
const auth = useAuth();
const login = auth.login;

Why curly brackets {}? - Because this is object destructuring.

You‚Äôre saying: ‚ÄúFrom the object returned by useAuth(), extract the login property and store it in a variable called login.‚Äù

//--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

1.2 What makes a Hook different from a normal function?

A normal function:

function add(a, b) {
  return a + b;
}

Runs the same way every time, React doesn‚Äôt care when or how you call it

A Hook like useContext:

const value = useContext(AuthContext);

Is tracked by React, Is tied to the component render cycle, Reads from React‚Äôs internal memory

Triggers re-renders when values change

üëâ React must know exactly when and where it‚Äôs called.

//-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

1. What is React Context?
Simple definition - Context is a way to share data globally across components without passing props manually at every level. It solves prop drilling.

2. The problem Context solves (prop drilling)

Without Context:
App
 ‚îî‚îÄ Layout (needs user)
     ‚îî‚îÄ Page
         ‚îî‚îÄ Component
             ‚îî‚îÄ Button (needs user)

You would need:
<App user={user}>
  <Layout user={user}>
    <Page user={user}>
      <Component user={user}>
        <Button user={user} />

3. What Context actually is (important)

Context is not magic. A context is just: A container, With a unique identity, That holds a value

Created by: const MyContext = createContext(defaultValue);

4. The 3 parts of Context (memorize this)
Every context has: Context object, Provider, Consumer (useContext)

5. Step-by-step with code
5.1 Create the context
const AuthContext = createContext<AuthContextType | undefined>(undefined);
This: Creates a context ‚Äúchannel‚Äù
Default value = undefined

5.2 Provide the value
<AuthContext.Provider value={{ user, loading, login, logout }}>
  {children}
</AuthContext.Provider>


This:Makes the value available To all components below

5.3 Consume the value
const context = useContext(AuthContext);

This: Reads the current value From the nearest Provider above

6. Why Context is NOT global state

Context: Does not store data itself Just passes data down, The data actually lives in: useState(...), Context only exposes it.

7. What are <> here? In this line:

const AuthContext = createContext<AuthContextType | undefined>(undefined);

The <> mean: - ‚ÄúTell TypeScript what type of value this context will hold.‚Äù

This context will hold: AuthContextType | undefined, 
Initially, its value is: undefined

//-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Async/Await/Timeout example

Timeout will hold the particular function and procees with rest of the lines.
Await will hold the function itself till the promise

//Example 
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<body>
<h1>JavaScript async / await</h1>
<h2 id="demo"></h2>
<h2 id="demo2"></h2>
<p>Wait 3 seconds (3000 milliseconds) for this page to change.</p>

<script>
async function myDisplay() {
  let myPromise = new Promise(function(resolve) {
    setTimeout(function() {resolve("I love You !!");}, 6000);
  });
  setTimeout(function() {document.getElementById("demo2").innerHTML = "2000 timeout";}, 2000);
  document.getElementById("demo2").innerHTML = "Before Await";
  setTimeout(function() {document.getElementById("demo2").innerHTML = "2nd 2000 timeout";}, 4000);
  document.getElementById("demo").innerHTML = await myPromise;
  document.getElementById("demo2").innerHTML = "After Await";
  setTimeout(function() {document.getElementById("demo2").innerHTML = "3rd 2000 timeout";}, 2000);
}

myDisplay();
</script>

</body>
</html>

